00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:53.760
to 15 seconds of duration. While 10 seconds is&nbsp;
still better than 8 seconds we had with Veo 3.1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:59.920
and might be perfectly fine for a TikTok clip,&nbsp;
it gives any film director or editor a massive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:06.960
headache when pacing a proper narrative film. But&nbsp;
honestly, I don't care what technical constraints&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:13.280
Veo might have for capping clips at 10 seconds, and&nbsp;
I certainly wasn't going to bottleneck the other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:20.000
models just to level the playing field for them.&nbsp;
Secondly, as always, we allowed only one or two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:27.600
generation attempts uh per scene for each model.&nbsp;
The prompts were specific and detailed enough that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:34.720
a mature model should deliver exactly what we&nbsp;
wanted without forcing us to develop calluses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:43.120
from spamming the "generate" button. Last but not&nbsp;
least, I'm a huge advocate for hybrid workflows.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:48.640
You should absolutely deploy a high-end, more&nbsp;
expensive model for your critical narrative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:56.800
moments like close-up dialogue or a subtle micro&nbsp;
expressions and then jump to a different engine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:04.960
for, say, a wide-angle car chase sequence. Sometimes&nbsp;
the choice is driven by budget constraints. Other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:12.800
times, a specific model is simply better suited for&nbsp;
a particular type of shot physics. All right. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:20.080
which model gets our official stamp of approval?&nbsp;
If we are focusing strictly on raw quality&nbsp;&nbsp;

